<Review>This location is a very good burger place that has an understated appearance. Small, simple, and with minimal decor but with better food than its looks would suggest. With plain brown commercial paper towel rolls for napkins and concrete floors the only real downside of this location is how it presents itself. The burgers and onion rings at this place are very good and they offer a small number of beers on tap. The price is reasonable when one considers the quality and proportions on offer. Given how easy it is to overlook I would consider this location something of a hidden gem, although the local students probably know it well. Anyone looking for burgers in the area should consider giving it a try.</Review><pics>None</pics>< Resp>

<text>Food and wait server were fantastic but it was all the other non food things that turns me off of this place.

1. They share a wall with a nail saloon, the smell was over powering inside the bistro and had to move outside. They only had 2 table with 3 chairs at each.

2. To many tables inside leaves no room to walk around comfortably. There weren't too many people inside but if it was busy, forget about it.

3. Drinks served in a 'to-go' cup with wait service and the server had take your cup for refills since the drinks were behind the counter.

4. Wasteful quantity of food; there were 2 of us and ordered the only size basket of fries. It was 3 lbs of fries! we couldn't even finish 1/2 of it; waste of money and food! I don't know about their other items but it is served a la carte so you if you want a side with your sandwich you have no choice in what size you get.

You won't be disappointed with the hamburgers as they were delicious.< /text>< pictures>

< text>
In the world of burger mathematics lies the formula to the recipe of a place where the burger=B is to the power of 3, or scientifically speaking B cubed, or B^3, lets not forget mathematically explained 1(BxBxB) =(hence) Bulldog Burger Bistro. This my lady's and gentlemen is the burgers of all burger places. Yes, crowded into the Bulldog Plaza shopping mall hides the holly cow cannoli, the grand finally of the finales. This is no ordinary place though, fight your way through the tight parking space and this is where you'd find The King of Burger King, it's where he hangs out when he's not shooting for BK commercials. Every now and then Ronald from McDonald's comes in to get a real burger when he's "really" hungry after eating his .25 lbs burger, and In and Out came in and out of this place before they became "In and Out," it truly is like Carl before giving birth to Carl Junior. This my friends is where Rally's checkered out and brought burgers into Eureka! Now visually speaking they aren't there yet, they're right where those above where before they became how they've become, before visual appeals were more important than the food that's become the dodo of the poopoo. Please don't let the visual appeal fool you though, the place is currently going through some renovations, with that set aside, this is how good the burgers are at this place. It is awesomely amazing!, they definitely crossed their t(s) and dotted their i(s) when it came to the food. So if you want to stimulate and highly intensify your frontal operculum and the anterior insula(this is part of your brain people), then I challenge you to come to this place where you'll find each characters above dancing together in harmony to something they can all enjoy. You too can dance in harmony and sing Kumbaya so what are you waiting for? Go-on, C'mon now... Carry on...<//text>

<text>This place makes their food with love! You can taste it in every bite.

If you're coming here for anything it's likely their friend chicken... And you should not skip that at all. It's lightly breaded and cooked to Golden perfection. I love friend chicken, had it from every place under the sun, and this place has something special with their recipe.

Was there for the chicken, and stayed for brunch! Well, I had to come back the next day. But the smell of them cooking bacon was driving me nuts! So we came back the next day, and I very much regret not ordering the eggs Benedict with the pork. My wife let me try hers and it was incredible.

I love eggs Benedict, and was worried this place might be trying too hard in this regard. But it was a mistake... I wanted to eat the whole thing!

If you have the time (and money) to make this place work, it's worth a visit of you're around the area.</text></record>

<text>Food is amazing.  Selection wonderfully curated.  However as a resident in a small town that loves and appreciates everything local, I always wanted to love this place.  I gave it shot after shot and I'm done.  Disappointing considering the few options we have in town.

If you're looking for couture food on the way to your wine tour by all means stop in and eat and drink and tip well.

If you live in Forestville, well, I don't have to say it because we already know, but this place isn't here for us.  Rosa's and Carr's and Tiny Town will charge you less and appreciate you more.  None of those are gourmet, but they are cooked with love and I appreciate all of them far more.

Also full truth the friend chicken is over rated.

Monday is "locals night" but we don't know a single neighbor that's been and gone back.

<GmapID>0x80843cb695f962ed:0xe917d6019e53a3b7</GmapID>< UserId.>
115621030401501499670<//UserId.>
<review>I really wanted to love this place as I work close by, my girlfriend loves fried chicken, and my customers are always asking for restaurant referrals. I rarely write bad reviews, but I feel compelled.

I decided to surprise my girlfriend on Mothers' Day and dropped by to get the chicken box to go, which takes 30 minutes--something I expected. I got busy at work and hadn't had time to call ahead.

I ordered at the counter. It was noisy, so I leaned forward to hear the waitress, at which point I was sternly admonished not to lean on the counter. OK, sorry. I told her I'd like to sit at the bar and have a drink. She said, "All the seats are taken," even though one remained empty the entire time I was there. She proceeded to sit me in the otherwise empty dining room, failing to take my drink order even though I made it clear I would like to order one. I was then promptly ignored.

About ten minutes later, a young waiter came by. I tried to order from him, but it turns out he was an underage busser. No problem; he quickly summoned a waitress. She took my drink order. Five minutes later, she returned with the first of my ($8!) beers. It had about three inches of foam on it. I said nothing, but she promised to return to top it off "once it settles." OK, fine. But she never returned.

Still waiting for my chicken, I decided to enjoy a second beer. Since my glass had been empty for some time and no one had bothered to check on me, I decided to go to the counter to order it. Before I could speak, I was rudely told, "Your order isn't ready yet." She turned to walk away, but I managed to place the order first. The beer was delivered by a different, thankfully friendlier, waitress.

The chicken arrived at my table. I tried to pay, but was advised that they didn't take AmEx. OK, fine. I reached for another card, but before I could pull it out, she walked away.

But what about the food? Well, I must say that what I heard about the chicken is true. It's beautifully crunchy and perfectly seasoned. The box came with nine pieces. But here's the problem(s).

The four biscuits were just average and a bit dry. The two tiny ramekins of honey butter were absolutely tasteless. We had to make our own.  It also came with two pints of sides. Oddly, both were the same. The black-eyed pea salad was so woefully underseasoned that we had to make our own vinaigrette to dress it up.

The final insult came in the form of chicken wings. There were a couple of small, cut up pieces of breast and two thighs, but buried under that were FIVE chicken wings. Seriously? For $45 (!), I wouldn't expect more than two in that box.

In the end, I was left feeling ripped off and disrespected. I know the chef worked at Ad Hoc, but come on. It's just fried chicken. If you want to charge Napa Valley prices in Forestville--the entire menu is grossly overpriced--you need to step up your game.

In the end, one star because you can't give zero, plus one because the chicken itself is really, really good. I may give it a second chance, but there are so many great restaurants who appreciate my business, it might be a while.</review></record>

<Text>Backyard hosted our rehearsal dinner recently. The food and atmosphere were fantastic. The process of working with their events planner to coordinate contracts, schedules, and options was a nightmare. I did not hear back for months after sending my deposit and was told that it was because they were busy and told to relax. I did not receive a final contract and even though I had email agreement that the start time of our dinner was 5:30, the restaurant was not ready when the guests arrived and I was told that I had the start time wrong. My guests were told to stand on the sidewalk beside a busy road even though their tables were ready with water on them.

The manager I had been dealing with the entire time belittled me when I brought up my concern and requested that my guests could sit at the tables even though the food and drinks weren't ready yet, saying "I know that you're stressed out because you're getting married..." and "We do a ton of these events...we know what we're doing..." I was almost in tears on the night of my rehearsal dinner. To boot, they could not figure out how to turn on their sound system and play the playlist I had spent lots of time assembling, playing the wrong music, revealing my first dance songs to all my guests.

When I showed the management the email where we had agreed on the start time of 5:30 and not 6:00 thereby proving that they were not ready on time, the owner told me that this was "just a miscommunication" - did not acknowledge that they had made a mistake, did not apologize for not sending me a final contract, and basically made a ton of excuses to justify their actions. They did not make any attempt to make up for their mistakes...so I just paid the bill with the mandatory 18% gratuity and called it a night.

My impression of this restaurant is that they take their food very seriously, perhaps sacrificing the time they have to plan events, and they take out this stress on their guests.</Text><Pictures>None</Pictures><Resp>None<//Resp><GmapID>0x80843cb695f962ed:0xe917d6019e53a3b7< /GmapID></record></dataset><record>

<UserId.>106991149670163563586<//UserId.><Name>Jae</Name><Date>1573605654111</Date><Rating>5< /Rating><text>Of my decades years of dental care, this practice is by far my greatest find, and needless to say, my favorite. The first time I met Dr. Sepi, I was impressed by his serene presence and air of integrity. After my xrays, he thoroughly explained what I needed, prioritizing the order of care recommended. They outlined his recommendations in a tabular format for easy reference. I left the office that first day, feeling like I had made a great "find."

Since then I have replaced my 30 yr old crowns. I was shocked at how non-traumatic the removal of my old crowns was. My new crowns are so natural and beautiful looking! I have two sisters who are office managers in dental practices in another state, and they are equally impressed with them. < Review>
I was told 1:45 hrs to get 5 tires installed, with 2 cars ahead of me.  as I was walking out, they realized there was just one car ahead, so told me come by earlier.  I said I'll be back in an hour- they said ok.  I came after 1 hr, to realize they hadn't started on my car yet.  once they did, they took another 2 hours.  and it was agonizing 2 hours (of actual work time) as I watched them install 5 tires, with less than 1 minute of "free car inspection" and 5 minutes of "free alignment check" only (but took 30+ minutes for this alone).  workers got distracted, stopped working on my car to chit chat with other workers working on different cars, went to go pick up a phone call then stayed at the desk for a while.  when workers were working on my car they moved quite slowly, almost deliberately slow (except for one guy who was mostly working on another car but came over on his own to work on my car when previous worker had just left).  workers and operations seem very inefficient.  quality?  not sure how I can judge quality for installing 5 tires in 2 hours of work time.  there was one guy working on my car, then he took a call and someone else was told to work on my car, then another guy came to finish things up because the 2nd guy had just left.  I was cringing the whole time as I watched this inefficient operation go on.  and then I saw a bmw on a lift come down off the lift, with the bottom of the car making contact with the lift as it was reversing.  the employee stopped, looked around while inside the car as to seek help, then other workers in the vicinity yelled out "you're good".  nobody except the driver and myself noticed the bottom of the car hit the lift, and I saw the plastic on the bottom rip and stick out.  if you own bmv 5bkd264 or 5bkd624- check the bottom.  I'm personally not upset- as I don't have full context.  but 2 hours (actual work time) for 5 tires is a waste of time for me and waste of time and $ for the shop.  the guys were friendly enough, but seems like operation management, communication between employees (when they transfer work to another worker) needs a whole lot of work.  i'm only posting this since it looks like the owner/manager reads this.

I will be trying a different shop when the time does come to replace tires for my other vehicles.< /Review>

<userid>113142283417828320394<//userid><name>Benjamin Wasserott< /name><date>1549812538063<//date><rate>5<//rate>< text>
Absolutely my wife and I had a fantastic time staying here. The building is an old mansion which gives a quaint atmosphere that you're walking do somebody's well-designed house. We stayed the Hollywood room which was spacious and tucked away at the top of the stairs. The chef makes fresh breakfast in the morning at a communal table. Great coffee great company great prices. This is one of those hidden gems in LA. Stay here if you were going to be visiting one of the many consulates in the area since they are literally a 10 to 20 minute walk away. I would stay here again and again and again.<//text>

I stayed at this place because it was cheap and close to where I needed to go. It's a mom and pop place and run like one. They give you the kitchen and most of the ground floor to work with. It's not beautiful but it is relatively clean and well maintained. The major downsides were that the WiFi doesn't work well, the room is tiny (8x9ft,the bed takes up most of the room space), the fruit in the basket was somewhat old and rotten, and the people in charge were not always accessible except during daylight hours. Not bad but you get what you pay for.< /text>

They had several other vehicles that fit my needs and were the same size as my Explorer, but they would not allow me to take them because they were not Fords. Had I known this- I would have called Enterprise ahead of time to make sure they had a vehicle that actually fit my needs, or not even gotten a rental at all.<//Text>

Visiting San Diego, on Saturday my new Ford SUV lost power and began to shake. We were towed by Ford to Perry for warranty service.

The best of times, the worst of times. Patrick the service rep is extremely good. He immediately diagnosed an internal coolant leak from head failure. He put us in a rental right away, moments before Enterprise closed. He was exceptional.

Once taken back to service though, Perry's techs misdiagnosed it as just a bad spark plug. They replaced the plug filled the empty coolant and gave the vehicle back to me. The band-aid lasted long enough for me drive home. By Monday it was misfiring and the check engine light was on.

Currently, I'm on my third dealer. Perry was first. The second dealer agreed with Patrick at Perry that it was a coolant leak in the head, but said they could not get to such a major repair for a month. The SUV is at the third Ford dealer now. There's some hope they will fix it. They did notice it misfires on cold starts and the coolant is low. We'll find out soon enough what they do.  I can't hold Perry responsible for Ford's unreliable product, or my unbelievable travails at other dealers.  On the other hand, if the guys in back at Perry has listened to their service rep Patrick it could have been fixed there. Might have been nice.</Review>

Thank you, Eric and Mario and Omar!!! I had been considering buying a new car for some time. I had test driven three other models of cars and Ford was the last one for me to test drive before making my decision.
I am so thankful I did the comparison driving and found Eric when I came to Perry Ford. I have not met a more knowledgeable sales person of his model cars but also the competitors. When I brought up things I liked about the other models, Eric acknowledged the aspect and showed me how Ford was different and better, or how Ford was similar with more. He helped me narrow down what was most important to me in the vehicle and helped me find it. He was not a pressure salesman in any way. If he had been, I would have left immediately. He encouraged me to think about it because he wanted me to LOVE the car I would be driving for a long time.
When I finally decided (I test drove several cars with Eric), Mario stepped in to find the best deal, with the discounts and other opportunities available through Ford. Additionally, Mario shopped around to find the absolutely best APR for the amount I needed to finance.
When we settled on the price, Omar put the paperwork together, shopped again for more local rebates, discounts, etc. He was able to reduce the price even more. He was extremely helpful and thorough in talking through the contract with me making sure I understood everything before asking me to sign it.
I cannot speak highly enough of the team at Perry Ford in National City. Each person knew what they were talking about and did not make empty promises. Each has followed through in every way. I feel I have a new automobile community.
I would recommend them without hesitation.  Thanks, guys! I love my platinum Ford Edge!!!<//text>

Initially the noise could only be heard while in ‚Äúpark‚Äù, and eventually graduated to all gears. On 2/1/19 I made an appointment (@ 8:30 AM) to have the vehicle inspected. He acknowledged the noise and had the vehicle inspected again. 45 minutes later he said he‚Äôs not sure what the sound was and was going to get in contact with a Ford Engineer to see what it might be. He also stated in the mean time he will see if any other Explorers were making the same noise (to see if it was a normal sound). On approximately2/10/19 or 2/11/19 Kim called me and said they had spoken with the Ford Engineers and were told the noise was not normal. She also stated they were not able to duplicate the noise with any other Explorer. I made another appointment to have the vehicle inspected on 2/15/19.  So on 2/15/19 I dropped the vehicle off at 8:30 AM. Again at approximately 2 PM Kim called me and stated they weren‚Äôt able to find any issues with the car and the sound it was making was considered NORMAL! I then spoke with the shop Foreman and he reiterated what Kim said . The sound was NORMAL and there were no issues. I went back and forth with him for a few minutes before I escalated the call to the Service Dept. Supervisor Bill Haas. <Rating>1</Rating><Review>About a year ago, we leased a Ford Edge from Perry Ford, and put a $15,500 cash down payment on it. Recently, we decided to upgrade to an Explorer. After a week of phone calls from Aldo, we finally go in to the dealership. We asked, first thing, how much of the down payment would transfer. We were told that it was dependent on the car that we chose. At one point, a dealer demo Explorer with 4,500 miles was offered to us. We asked what the discount for the 4,500 miles would be, and they said that there was none... so they were trying to sell us a USED car for a BRAND NEW CAR price, stating that since it was the demo, it had never been registered with the DMV,and was, therefore, new. Obviously, we declined.

We finally found an Explorer with all of the features we wanted. We asked again how much of the $15,500 would transfer, and he did a lot of beating around the bush and asked to run our credit to figure out financing options for the new Explorer. We told him not to run our credit, because it was irrelevant if we weren't going to get enough of the down payment to transfer. Finally, he came out with a paper about the financing options for the Explorer, based on average credit, and a very carefully-worded explanation of how the Edge would be "taken care of", we would owe nothing on it, and he quickly tried to talk about the Explorer again. We asked about the Edge's down payment transferring (seriously, broken record, anyone?) and he finally admitted that it wouldn't. I asked why he had stated that it would over the phone, and he blamed it on his manager, saying that the manager had told him that it would, and then went back on it and said that now it wouldn't. We asked for our keys back, and he went to get them and the manager. The manager said that a down payment is only good for one car, and doesn't transfer. Okay, I can understand that. That makes sense, if that's your policy. What I don't understand is why Aldo said that it would, over the phone, and then hounded me for a week to come in, after giving me false information.... and then when we finally get there, he kept putting off the questions about the down payment until we found the car we wanted.

It's extremely insulting that he assumed he could lie to me, hook us with a car, and then have us so starry-eyed over the Explorer that we'd sign away the Edge and flush that $15,500 down the toilet without hesitation. Seriously?

Like i said, I can understand not transferring the down-payment. < Review>
Just don't go here. Unless you either like wasting time after your purchase, or you have some strange desire to get into the business version of an unhealthy relationship....I'd stay away. Long story short, they took almost 9 weeks to CORRECTLY activate my enhanced GPS tracking service that I paid extra for at time of purchase. All after being told repeatedly that it would be taken care of, yet I had to keep being persistent because it wasn't being handled. Then I was told that I'd get 2 years of free maintenance. I said I wanted something in writing with specifics because the follow through on words had been brutally awful up to that point. I was informed that I would receive my documentation of "free maintenance" including what that would even entail - my car surpasses the quarts that most "free" oil changes cover. It's been another month, and I have received no such documentation. BUT - I will say this: after finally getting my GPS set up properly I decided I'd let their actions speak because I'm tired of their words, so I committed to not call about the maintenance. And my life has been SO relieved of stress. Hahaha. Whatever, I'll go to Mossy instead. They have a Quick Lane and better reviews anyway.

Great service all around as I purchased my new Mustang! Gustavo and Breanna were both super friendly and awesome to deal with! So were Mario and Celia. Everyone, actually but those 4 specifically as I had the most contact with them.

Unfortunate update here: The buying process was still A+. Unfortunately, I had some add-on items that I purchased and it's been a major headache getting activation on one of the items - rather not specify what in this forum. I have visited the dealership personally to get this resolved and was told it'd be handled the following Monday. That was a couple weeks ago. Nothing happened. Went back in this Monday and watched as an employee entered my info to get activation on this service I purchased. It only took 10 minutes tops so I'm not sure why I had to wait a whole month and be so pesty to just get it done. But then, the info was entered incorrectly so my service is active but it's active on a different car on the Perry lot. I called again last night, about out of patience at this juncture and was told this would be resolved first thing in the morning. It is now after 11 a.m. the next day and I"ve heard nothing. There were also some non-returned phone calls during all of this. This is WAY BEYOND NOT COOL. Perry Ford is great at getting customers, apparently they do not put the same effort into keeping them. That's some free, constructive criticism right there for you. The most irritating thing about this whole ordeal is that it truly feels like I'm the only one this is important to. Newsflash: I just bought a brand new car, I'm not supposed to have car stress for quite a while now.</Review>
